Analysis of Hacker Network Forum Data

ANZ Presentation

Hendrik A. Dreyer

16 May 2019

Introduction

Hacker News is a social news website focusing on computer science and entrepreneurship. It is run by Paul Grahams investment fund and start up incubator, Y Combinator. In general, content that can be submitted is defined as anything that gratifies ones intellectual curiosity.

Task 1: Analyse the data

YCombinator.com has released the contents of its online forum to Google. The forum content is freely available as a public BigQuery data set as bigquery-public-data.hacker_news..

There are 4 tables listed under the hacker_news entry:

  • Analysis of the comments, full_201510 and stories table:
    • First entry - 10/09/2006 @ 6:21pm (UTC)
    • Last entries - 10/13/2015 @ 8:44am (UTC)
    • The ids in the stories table = ids in full_201510 (where type = story)
    • The ids in the comments table = ids in full_201510 (where type = comment)
    • The number of stories in in the stories table = number of entries in the full_201510 table (where type = story)
    • The first polling timestamp - 03/01/2008 @ 8:34pm (UTC)

Note: There is a discrepancy of 502 records between the number of records in the comments table and the number of record in the full_201510 table that is labelled comment

Therefore, the stories and comments tables are subsets of the full_210510 table. We can remove them from the analysis and focus only on the table labelled, full.

The full table schema

  • The full table:
    • First entry - 2006-10-09 18:21:51 UTC
    • Last entry - current
    • 26821 missing timestamp entries (total empty entries)

The type field

The records are differentiated by the type field.

  • The type field is a nominal categorical variable which have types:
    • comment - (16,548,891 entries)
    • story - (3,301,680 entries)
    • job - (11,924 entries)
    • pollopt - (12,019 entries)
    • poll - (1,760 entries)

Note: There is no type comment_ranking in the full table.

Poll : These are online polls that are run regarding various topics.
Pollopt : These are different options available for the polls (Yes/No; Male/Female; Paper/Digital)
story : These are stories posted by users
comments : These are comment by users on stories
job : These are online job ads

Bad field naming

  • by is a sql key word. In order to use it you have to alias the table and then reference it through the alias. Otherwise, SQL reports an error.
  • Rename by to author or " username"

The time and timestamp fields

  • The time field (INT) - seconds since the great epoch - 1970
  • The timestamp field (TIMESTAMP) can keep track of time zones

The parent field

  • This field references the id to its parent record (another comment - linked list/graph)

The descendants field

  • Hold the number of descendant (comments?) for the story and polls

The ranking field

  • This field has only NULL values

Field descriptions

  • The type field lists the wrong types in its description
  • Rename type description to Type of entry
  • by - The username of the items author. Rename to The username
  • timestamp - Rename to Entry submitted timestamp
  • text - rather rename to comment
  • Rename descendant desctiprion to Number of comments
  • id - Add the words auto increment

Summary

  • 6 x Integer fields
  • 2 x Boolean
  • 5 x String fields (1 is probably a BLOB)
  • 1 x Timestamp

Task 2: Identify any characteristics of the data that could make it either easy or challenging for ANZ to use the data.

  • Data Issues - Forum context (data contains insights: behavioural, media, sentiment)
    • Stories are posted mostly as url links. This makes collecting the story matter more difficult (web crawling/scraping)
    • Text mining - rely on the title fields to get a sense of what the story is about
    • The value of the forum data lies mostly in the comments
    • Comments are captured in a blob and makes it difficult to cross-correlate with other data sources
    • Forum content is too wide and open
  • Optimization recommendations
    • The time field is redundant - remove
      • (INT) - 64 bits: (19,890,873 x 8 bytes) / 1024 bytes = 155 MB
    • The ranking field is redundant - remove
      • (INT) - 64 bits: (19,890,873 x 8 bytes) / 1024 bytes = 155 MB
    • All fields are NULLABLE - causes 26821 empty entries)
      • (7.4 GB / 19,890,873 rows) = (372 bytes/row * 26821 empty rows) / 1024 bytes = 9.7 MB
    • All data is stored in one table - split up into relational tables and normalize.
      • Gets rid of type field: BigQuery suggest saving 164.4 MB
    • Rename the field by to something sensible - e.g.UserName
    • There are plenty of duplicate values in the poll options (e.g.yes/no)
  • Inconsistencies between tables
    • Several inconsistencies between all four the tables
    • time, timestamp, time_ts
    • by, author
    • mismatching type categories
  • Recommendations
    • Design new HN DB
    • Pros:
      • Relational layout - easier to understand
      • Might have improved performance
      • Save disk space - enforce constraints
    • Cons:
      • Will it really improve performance? (@ +- 2 submits/second)
      • Multiple joins needed

DIKW - Data /Information / Knowledge / Wisdom

  • Hierarchy
    • Helps to contextualize information flow
    • Information symmetry/asymmetry
    • Shapes analytics narrative

Task 3: Identify some interesting findings in the data

  • Technique used
    • NLP - Natural Language Processing
    • Text Mining
    • Create word cloud of most frequent words used around a central topic/word
# Load
library("tm")
library("SnowballC")
library("wordcloud")
library("RColorBrewer")

create_word_map <- function(path_and_filename, max_words){
  
  #Create Corpus
  text <- readLines(path_and_filename)

  docs <- Corpus(VectorSource(text))

  #inspect(docs)

  toSpace <- content_transformer(function (x , pattern ) gsub(pattern, " ", x))
  docs <- tm_map(docs, toSpace, "/")
  docs <- tm_map(docs, toSpace, "@")
  docs <- tm_map(docs, toSpace, "\\|")

  # Convert the text to lower case
  docs <- tm_map(docs, content_transformer(tolower))
  # Remove numbers
  docs <- tm_map(docs, removeNumbers)
  # Remove english common stopwords
  docs <- tm_map(docs, removeWords, stopwords("english"))
  # specify your stopwords as a character vector
  docs <- tm_map(docs, removeWords, c("donxt", 
                                      "isnxt",
                                      "just",
                                      "can",
                                      "will",
                                      "think",
                                      "one")) 
  # Remove punctuations
  docs <- tm_map(docs, removePunctuation)
  # Eliminate extra white spaces
  docs <- tm_map(docs, stripWhitespace)
  # Text stemming
  # docs <- tm_map(docs, stemDocument)

  dtm <- TermDocumentMatrix(docs)
  m <- as.matrix(dtm)
  v <- sort(rowSums(m),decreasing=TRUE)
  d <- data.frame(word = names(v),freq=v)
  #head(d, 10)

  set.seed(1489)
  wordcloud(words       = d$word, 
            freq        = d$freq, 
            min.freq    = 1,
            max.words   = max_words, 
            random.order= FALSE, 
            rot.per     = 0.35, 
            colors=brewer.pal(8, "Dark2"))
}
